Below 7 MeV/Nucleon:  Measurements and Analysis of

x4freetext: Decay Analysis to Obtain the Precursor Decay
Contribution.
Department of Physics
Sir Syed College, and 3 Dsn College.
- By Author:  this Experiment has Been done with a View
To Studying Complete and Incomplete Fusion in
Heavy-Ion-Induced Reactions.  Excitation Functions For
Several Reactions Induced by 12-C-5+ Ions on 165-Ho at
Incident Energies from 55 to 80 MeV have Been Measured
Using the Activation Technique.  The Analysis of the
Data has Been done Using the Codes "Alice 91" and
"Cascade".  Significant Contributions from Both the
Complete and the Incomplete Fusion Channels have Been
Observed.  Further, in the Case of the Reaction (C,P3N)
Considerable Contribution from the Decay of Higher
Charge Isobar Precursor has Been Observed.
Nuclear Science Center, New Delhi
Rolled Natural Holmium Foils (PURITY >99.9%) Of
Thickness 2 Milligramm/Cm**2 were Used As Target. The
A Transmission Method Based on the Measurements of the
Energy Lost by a Particles While Passing Through the
Sample has Been Utilized to Measure the Thickness of
Each Target Individually.  Individual Samples Backed by
Aluminum Catcher Foils of Thickness 1 Milligramm/Cm**2.
The Samples were Irradiated with a 12-C-5+ Beam
Of Current 30 Na at Four Different Energies:  55, 62,
71, and 80 MeV.
The Irradiations were Performed For 4-5 H
Duration Each.
As Well As from the Counts of the Two
Rutherford Monitors Kept at + and - 30 Degrees with
Respect to the Beam Direction.  They were Found to
Agree with Each Other Within 5%.
See Sample.
Error in the Incident Beam Energy has Been
Determined by Calculating the Energy Spread in Half of
The Sample Thickness.
The Error in the Thickness of the Sample
Material is Expected to be <1%.
It is Estimated That the Beam Current Fluctuations May
Introduce <3% Error. The Statistical Fluctuations in
Efficiency is Estimated to be <2%.
In Order to Minimie the Loss Due to the Nuclei
Recoiling Out of the Target, the Sample and the Catcher
Foil were Counted Together.
Last checking has been done.

x4freetext: The Cross Section is Cumulative
- By Authors: the Contribution of 171-Lu Isotope from
The Precursor Decay of 171-Hf at 62 and 71 MeV is
Expected to be Negligible Because of the Relatively
High Value of Threshold Energy For the Latter.
However, at 80 MeV, Measured Cross Section For 171-Lu
Is Cumulative.
